post_text:
Like so many other things affected by COVID-19, the LaFayette Central School District’s Class of 2020 saw its senior trip go up in smoke, as the pandemic forced society’s hand and greatly limited travel and large gatherings in order to maintain safety.

Instead of moping about their misfortune, the Class of 2020 saw an opportunity to produce some good out of its situation. Sitting on a tidy sum of money that had been earmarked for the senior trip, the graduating class (led by its class officers, pictured here) put their heads together and tried to come up with some institutions who might be able to use that money to great effect.

They settled on one of the best, making a $1,300 donation to the Upstate Golisano Children’s Hospital. It was an amazingly kind act, borne out of awful circumstances.

As COVID continues to impact our collective routines, perhaps few groups were more affected in that capacity than this year’s seniors. A big shout-out to the Class of 2020 for making an impact during tough times, and turning a negative into an overwhelming positive!

post_text:
Community reminder:

The parade honoring seniors will be held beginning at 6 p.m. this evening, and originating at the Onondaga Nation Ice/Lacrosse Arena located on Route 11.

The parade will start at the Onondaga Nation Arena at 6 p.m. and then head north on Route 11, left onto Route 11A Main Road through the Onondaga Nation, right onto Tully Farms Road, then left onto Route 20 to LaFayette, and then left onto Route 11 North, ending at LaFayette High School.

We ask that parade participants please adhere to social distancing requirements, remember to wear a mask, and avoid littering our beautiful community during the parade.

The Onondaga Nation has also requested that only Nation residents line the parade route through the Onondaga Nation to help prevent the spread of COVID-19.

To our graduates: Please remember to sit on the passenger side of the vehicle. We hope that we can count on our awesome community to show love and support for the Class of 2020!

April 15, 2020

Dear LaFayette School Community:

The district was approached by a group of thoughtful community members who would like to honor the class of 2020 in a special way with yard signs for students in our senior class. Please see the message below from the LaFayette Sports Boosters:

Since the school year is one for the history books and we are unsure of the unknown future, we wanted to provide a little something to honor the Class of 2020. We will be selling lawn signs to show our love and support.

Each sign is 18X24 and comes with a wire stake. A photo of the yard sign is included with this post. Signs cost $10.

All seniors will be receiving one for their house and thank you to some of the community who have submitted donations to help offset the cost.

If you are interested please contact The LaFayette Athletic Booster club, via email or Facebook. You can pay via PayPal (LaFayetteABC1@gmail.com) or check, cash.

Once these signs arrive we will make contact with families to arrange delivery (while observing social distancing rules to keep everyone safe!).

It is “Read Across America Week,” and the students at Grimshaw Elementary School are getting in on the fun!

They kicked things off on Monday by celebrating Dr. Seuss's birthday, and staff members and community volunteers took turns reading some of his famous books aloud to the students. The students in Ms. Pulverenti's class welcomed guest readers in the pictures you see below!

Here is the list of fun Dr. Seuss-themed events for Read Across America week:

Monday, March 2: Dr. Seuss’s Birthday/Read Across America Day / “Wear Your Red and White” Day

Tuesday, March 3: “Wear Your Crazy Socks to School”

Wednesday, March 4: “Wear Your Green to School”

Thursday, March 5: “Wear Your Red and Blue to School”

Friday, March 6: “Wear Your Favorite Pajama Day”

post_text:
Last week, LaFayette’s high school students celebrated the improvement in their performance when taking the STAR test for English language arts (ELA) and math.

The STAR test is a computer-based exam that monitors student progress and mastery of grade-level reading comprehension and math skills. Students take the STAR test three times a year, and their progress, growth, and achievement in said testing helps us make decisions that will best meet their needs.

In grade-level competitions, our sophomores and juniors grew the most on their STAR assessments, and we celebrated the performance of both classes with pizza parties! We also celebrated our RockSTARS - who were in the top 10% of growth and achievement in their grade levels - with star snacks, stickers, and a recognition celebration.

Congratulations to our students and staff on this wonderful achievement!

LaFayette Central School District
January 31 at 5:00 PM ·

GRAND OPENING LAFAYETTE HIGH SCHOOL

When: Rescheduled for Monday February 10th at 4:30 PM

Where: Cafeteria/Athletic Lobby

Dear LaFayette School Community and Staff:

Come out and celebrate the completion of major construction at LaFayette High School for the recent capital project approved by the voters in May 2017. We are so excited to share the following newly renovated spaces with our school community: New Kitchen, Serving Area, Renovations to the Cafeteria and Athletic Lobby, along with updates to the Wellness Center and Team Rooms. Here is the schedule of events:

4:30 PM - Ribbon Cutting Ceremony Serving Line Entrance

4:45 PM - Tour of Serving Line, Kitchen, Cafeteria, Athletic Lobby,
New Bench in the Hall of Fame, Wellness Center

5:00 PM - Cake and Punch Reception.
The After the Prom Party Fundraiser will also be selling hot dogs and other refreshments to help our Junior Class

The Boys Varsity Basketball team will host Fabius Pompey that evening - JV game starts at 5:00 PM followed by the Varsity Game. Come out and enjoy our newly renovated spaces and cheer on the Lancers!

Recently, syracuse.com compiled the graduation rates for every public high school in New York, revealing a 95% mark for the LaFayette Central School District! This marks the third year running that LCSD has achieved a graduation rate higher than 90%.

"At LaFayette, our goal is to help students achieve excellence in our school programs, while also providing a gateway for them to attain success in their future career and/or college programs as well," said Superintendent Jeremy Belfield. "I am incredibly proud of our students and staff for their commitment to excellence in academics!"

Over the holidays, students in Mallory Charpentier’s culinary classes looked to “give back” to an organization that serves one of the most noble causes of all: The Helping Hounds Dog Rescue!

Teachers and students got to work, baking up some homemade dog cookies that were cut out to form them out into fun shapes! Ms. Charpentier then delivered the snacks to the Helping Hounds branch near ShoppingTown Mall shortly before the holiday.

“I wanted to do a service project with the students, something that would see them give back to the community,” said Mallory. “The shelter was super appreciative!”

Great job by everyone! Pictured: Devon H., Brett B., and Christian D. helping roll and cut the snacks.

post_text:
Recently, the LaFayette Central School District’s “5 for 5 Food Drive” put the finishing touches on a successful holiday collection!

As the drive’s moniker indicates, the 5 for 5 drive challenged students from the LaFayette High School and Big Picture School to contribute either $5, or 5 non-perishable food items for collection (in exchange for in-class extra credit points), all of which benefit the LaFayette Outreach Food Pantry.

Normally run by Maura Daly-Picciotti, this year’s event was helmed by pinch-hitter Tim Baker. Mr. Baker himself leaned heavily on the exceptional work of two seniors, Lauren P. and Lily B., who led the charge in collecting over 500 food and toiletry items during the event!

Special thanks also go out to Halee A., who aided in the delivery of these supplies to the food pantry. The volunteers at LaFayette Outreach were “absolutely thrilled” with both the district’s efforts and results!

Grimshaw Elementary is getting in the holiday spirit.

To celebrate the holiday season and continue to build our school community, we are holding 5 Spirit Days, beginning Monday, December 16th through Friday, December 20th.

Monday, December 16th - “Hats Off” - for the Holidays, wear your favorite holiday hat, elf ears, etc.

Tuesday, December 17th - “Holiday Sock Party” - wear a pair of crazy holiday socks to school

Wednesday, December 18th - “Red and Green Day” - how much red and green can you wear?

Thursday, December 19th - “Ugly Holiday Apparel Day” - bring on the ugly sweaters/t-shirts,etc.

Friday, December 20th - “Pajama Day” - get in the spirit of wearing your favorite PJs to be comfy and cozy!!! (Please no slippers for safety reasons)

Note: There will be a sign-in/sign-out table in the foyer, and please make sure that the pick-up parent or guardian brings some identification

Last Tuesday, the Onondaga Nation School hosted a wonderful harvest dinnerl!

The school began serving meals at 10:45 a.m. and we did not stop serving until almost 1 p.m. All told, the school served over 430 meals for the event!

School faculty and staff helped prepare and serve a stunning assortment of food, including (but not limited to): Corn casserole, butternut squash, corn soup, chocolate chip pumpkin bread, and pumpkin fluff.

The dinner also hosted some fun prize events, including a basket raffle, bike raffle, and 50/50 fundraiser, all in support of end-of-the-year field trips for the students.

Congratulations are in order for several LaFayette High School students, who were recently selected to perform at the Onondaga County Music Educators Association (OCMEA) Senior High All-County Music Festival!

- Victoria K. - Band (ranked 10th in the county on flute!)
- Sarah W. - Chorus
- Aidan G. - Chorus
- Scott H. - Chorus

These students were selected based on their performance of rigorous audition material, for which they spent months preparing. Being selected for the all-county performance, especially in Onondaga County, is an impressive accomplishment!

The OCMEA concert will be held on Jan. 11 at 2 p.m. at West Genesee High School.

Last month, some Onondaga Nation School (ONS) students and staff were featured in a video created by the United States Tennis Association, highlighting Native American Heritage Month!

The video spot highlights ONS students taking tennis lessons Dr. Jennifer Kagan and ONS art teacher Chris Capella. Dr. Kagan founded Onondaga Nation’s branch of the National Junior Tennis Association 17 years ago. Today, students continue to meet after school, practicing at Tsha' Thon'nhes (the Onondaga Nation Pavilion) and learning more about the sport.

To view the video, click below!

Students and staff at the Onondaga Nation School (ONS) recently celebrated the school’s improvement in overall attendance in a very cool way.

Chiefs Shannon Booth and Jesse Lyons led the students in the “Stomp Dance” around the school, as a way of bringing everyone out to celebrate a great achievement! The procession went throughout the school, from room to room, before concluding in the gym.

In September of this year, ONS saw 24 students achieve perfect attendance for the month, followed by another 13 students in October!

In addition to the school-wide celebration, a notice of special recognition will be sent home, honoring the students who have had months of perfect attendance. On time and present… every day!

Please click below to see the students in action!

Hearty congratulations go out to LaFayette Central School District alumna Kate Racculia (class of ‘98), who recently saw her third book published! “Tuesday Mooney Talks to Ghosts” (Houghton Mifflin Harcourt) will be released on Oct. 8!

Want to celebrate the occasion? Stop by the Barnes & Noble in DeWitt (Erie Blvd.) where Kate will be holding a reading/signing event one week from today! (Friday, Oct. 11 at 6:30 p.m.).

Kate is the daughter of Jane (a retired Grimshaw teacher) and Mick, and currently resides in Bethlehem, PA. She teaches online for Grub Street, works at her local library, does private manuscript consults, and sings in the oldest Bach choir in America.

Join the excitement, and congratulations again to Kate! We hope to see you at the book signing!

Onondaga County Sheriff's Office
September 25, 2019 at 3:18 PM ·

Onondaga Nation School teacher, Mr. McCoy, had planned a bicycle outing with his 3rd grade class and reached out to the Onondaga County Sheriff's Office for a little bit of help. He wanted to be sure that the children in his class had an appropriately fitted helmet and knew the rules of the road when on a bicycle prior to their outing. Deputy Poland did a presentation with the 3rd graders on the rules of the road and bicycle safety as well as fitted each child with a new bicycle helmet. It's great to see different areas of the community coming together to make sure the children in Onondaga County are safe.

On the last day of May, the LaFayette Junior-Senior High School sent two groups to compete in Darien Lake's Music Festival!

At the festival, LaFayette’s senior high chorus (grades 9-12) competed in the “High School Mixed Choir” category, and the senior high band (grades 9-12) competed in the “Concert Band Class AA” grouping. During festival competition, students are given a performance evaluation by qualified adjudicators based on their performance.

Each group performed two musical selections, and two judges evaluated qualities such as spirit, style, expression, musicality, accuracy, technique, and interpretation. Both groups earned a rating of "Outstanding with Distinction," which is the highest rating a team can receive!

Congratulations to all of these students, who worked exceptionally hard in preparation for the event. It was great to see that dedication pay off during a fun day at Darien Lake!

Recently, the New York Association for Pupil Transportation (NYAPT) held a poster design contest to help raise awareness for school bus safety. The theme of this year’s competition was “Red Light Means STOP!” in accordance with the district’s (and state’s) increased focus on cracking down on motorists who attempt to pass stopped school bus signs.

Several students from the LaFayette Central School District entered the competition, and placed in the regional (Central New York) competition! The next step will be the statewide judging, which will take place this July during the NYAPT summer conference.

Congratulations to this year’s winners!

Division 1 (grades K-2)
First place: Leena Kolbeck

Division 2 (grades 3-5)
First place: Lynn Jones

Division 3 (grades 6-8)
First place: Caroline Davidson
Second place: Kiera Reed
Third place: Harlie Walker

Winning posters from each division in the statewide competition will earn the creator a cash prize and certificate, as well as an automatic bid for the national competition. Good luck at the state competition!

Recently, a couple of LaFayette “Battle of the Books” teams took top honors in regional competition!

At the outset, twelve teams (comprised of nearly 50 students from the third through sixth grades) competed in the local/school contest, answering Jeopardy-style questions based around 10 specific books. Each team had an adult coach to help them access the books through the library as they prepared for the contest.

The two LaFayette teams who won the school competition then went on to do “battle” in the Onondaga-Cortland-Madison BOCES regional contest. Both teams ended up placing there, as well!

Third/Fourth Grade Team (2nd Place):
Coach: Crystal Morel
Kennedy Harmatuk
Presley Homer
Amanda Lamon
Gianna Papworth

Fifth/Sixth Grade Team (1st Place):
Coach: Kelly Davidson
Caroline Davidson
Shayla Elem
Amelia Evans
Sophie Olrich

Congratulations to all of our teachers and students on a job well done!

Recently, some of the LaFayette High School and LaFayette Big Picture School’s students have been getting a feel for the professional life as they dive into their new internships!

The SECNY Federal Credit Union has opened a student-run Lancer Branch in the main office of the Junior/Senior High School. Big Picture students Randy, Kaia, and Jamus all have internships at the branch and Junior/Senior High School students Ben and Collin are also working at the SECNY Lancer Branch.

Presently, Jamus is the branch manager, Ben is the assistant manager, Kaia is the marketing representative, and Randy and Collin are the tellers. These five students will be working alongside a representative from SECNY to open and manage accounts, and some LaFayette teachers have already opened accounts and made deposits!

The students have been thrilled with their positions so far, and have been actively promoting the bank to their peers and teachers!

January 11, 2019 - For Immediate Release
LaFayette voters approve $3.1 million capital improvement project
On January 11 LaFayette Central School District voters approved the district’s $3.1 million capital
improvement project. 135 votes yes and 14 votes no.
Voters approved:
● Additional Security Cameras
● Campus Notification System
● Door Replacements
● Window Hardening
● Compartmentalization of Buildings Using Corridor Door Lock-Downs
● Masonry Repointing and Stair Replacement
The total cost of these enhancements comes to $3.1 million dollars; however, this project is eligible for
building aid through the New York State Education Department. The district is able to make these
improvements at no additional cost to our local property owners. Additional details about the capital
project are available on our website - click here.
